Club of Negative Interest Rates
BRUSSELS – For most of the last decade, central banks have made limited progress in countering strong global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the US Federal Reserve has maintained interest rates at zero while also undertaking multiple unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchases.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have followed the Fed’s lead, implementing their own versions of what is known as “quantitative easing” (QE).
But inflation has failed to gain any reasonable traction anywhere.
Although these countries have been battling deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — and economic performance — have diverged.
Now the US and UK growth is strong enough to allow for the exit of expansionary policies and higher interest rates, whereas the eurozone and Japan are increasing their QE and pushing policy long-term interest rates further into negative territory.
Why this difference?
Briefly, it is debt.
For decades, the US and UK have had current account deficits and thus are debtor nations, whereas the eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses and thus are creditor nations.
<span>&lt;span&gt;Negative interest rates benefit debtor nations but harm creditor nations, so the global economic crisis introduced negative interest rates that spurred recoveries in the US and the UK, but had little effect on the eurozone and Japan.&lt;/span&gt;</span>
&lt;s&gt;This is not an isolated phenomenon.&lt;/s&gt;
&lt;s&gt;So far, most creditor nations - countries with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland - have negative interest rates, not just for long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debts, but also for intermediate-term bonds.&lt;/s&gt;
&lt;s&gt;This is not good.&lt;/s&gt;
&lt;s&gt;Despite the ineffectiveness of low interest rates, central banks in these economies still adhere to this policy.&lt;/s&gt;
If you argue that QE or lowering interest rates can't deliver economic gains, they'll dismiss you by refuting the idea that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — which, on the surface, seems irrefutable.
In reality, it's full of holes.
Basic economics courses mention the oddity of the "backward-bending supply of savings curve": in certain environments, lower interest rates lead to more savings.
Because lower interest rates reduce the income of savers, they will cut spending, especially if they're saving for retirement.
All of this isn't denying the general rule — which forms the basis of modern monetary policy — that cutting interest rates stimulates consumption and other expenditures.
Only the impact differs because of the different debt conditions of the economies.
In a closed economy, every creditor has a debtor, so wherever creditors lose due to extremely low interest rates, debtors should benefit.
But in an economy with significant net foreign asset positions, creditors naturally outnumber debtors.
For a country with significant foreign debt, the situation is the opposite.
Therefore, monetary policy with interest rate lower bounds works differently in creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this mattered less because foreign asset positions were typically small (as a percentage of GDP).
But now, major industrialized economies have large and increasingly diverse foreign asset positions, partly because of the leverage that led to the global financial crisis in 2007–2008.
In fact, leverage continues to rise at the national level.
While current-account imbalances have moderated overall since the financial crisis began, they have not reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, deepening the divide with deficit economies.
<s>Some commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, had large current-account surpluses when oil prices were high, making them the main exceptions to the pattern of divergent foreign asset positions.
<s>Since June 2014, when world oil prices plunged, the wealth trends of these countries have reversed.
<s>Their export earnings plummeted — many falling by half — forcing them into deficits, relying on sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the commodity boom.
<s>A significant reduction in spending is now inevitable.
<s>Industrialized economies face a different set of challenges.
Their problem — to some extent, a luxury one — is to ensure that consumers spend the unexpected income from falling import prices.
But in creditor countries, negative interest rates do not seem to be advancing that goal; indeed, some of those with external surpluses are even increasing them.
This divergence exists within the eurozone as well.
Though the eurozone as a whole is a creditor economy, there are debtor countries within it.
Debtor economies like Spain and Portugal now have frequent current-account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
But traditional debtor countries have such high current-account surpluses that the asymmetry between debtor and creditor countries continues to increase.
Most strikingly, Germany's current-account surplus has climbed to nearly 8% of GDP since the financial crisis, meaning that its surpluses have exceeded historical totals accumulated up to that point.
Following current trends, Germany's creditor positions could grow from 60% of GDP to 100%.
Central bankers should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend toward central bank independence precisely because central banker们较少渴望刺激短期经济增长。
<s>But central bankers seem to lack patience, fretting over low inflation even as output gaps narrow and both the US and Japan achieved full employment.
<s>Central bankers in debtor countries must stop manipulating their economies with more monetary easing that may not be beneficial to production.
<s>Instead, they should allow recovery to develop on its own, even if it is slow, and wait for the base effects from falling oil prices to fade.
<s>ECB President Mario Draghi recently acknowledged that current monetary policy approaches may not be effective in today's global environment.
<s>But promising more of the same is not a solution.
